text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text_retweet:
yesterday i saw this post from a speaker whose posts i almost always love and it was so disappointing. in it, a man, suggested that #metoo was great *but* it was causing a divide among men and women so it was time for us to calm it all down (ie be less angry) and focus on bridge building between men and women.
.
i wanted to repost it and say something sarcastic like â€œi think the patriarchy and violence against women has caused more divides, historically, between men and women than #metooâ€
.
or i wanted to post something about how asking people to just â€œquiet it downâ€ and â€œfocus on positivityâ€ is just tone policing and how socially tone policing is another way that oppressors try to keep oppressed groups in line. something i am always learning more about from rachel cargle and something i used to be guilty of. i try harder now to remember anger is useful and not to ask people to be less angry about their oppression (!)
.
then i opened up my feed and rachel cargleâ€™s post saying all that much more eloquently was right there at the top ğŸ’™ğŸ™.
.
p.s. we can bridge build and be angry

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this resonated so deeply within me the moment i saw it.
something i have not shared on here before, and the loudest of my â€œmumbling miceâ€, i am a survivor. iâ€™m a survivor of decades of physical, emotional, mental and sexual abuse. i can say that now. i hid this from my family and friends. the shame, embarrassment and guilt were and are demons of the abuse i struggle with to this day. in fact, i struggle now, sharing this under the guise of a pseudonym.
i knew nothing about that relationship was right but the mental beating down and weakening held me there.
it wasnâ€™t until i inhaled that first small breath of fresh, almost-freedom air that i realized how toxic, how horrendous and how volatile my situation was.
two decades of abuse, of being battered and broken. i mustered the courage to walk away and have been putting my pieces back together...the way i want to be put back together. 
if anyone reading this right now is where i was, please heed my words.  i want you to muster your strength and courage, tell someone, formulate a plan and safely get out. do not be ashamed! do not be embarrassed! you did nothing wrong! you are strong and brave and you have done what you needed to do to survive to this point. this moment is the beginning of step two. take back your freedom. 
#survivor #youcandoit #empoweryourself #empowering #notjusttalkingtowomen #takeastand #metoo #selfloveisthebestlove #abusesurvivor

text:
the decent and the descent â€œcitius, altius, fortiusâ€ â€˜swifter, higher, strongerâ€™ -motto of the olympics

larry nassar, the champion harasser,
abuser, confuser, and chooser of
wicked deeds, having decreed 
by his actions that his needs are
above others and such.
for after all he has the postmodern
midas touch, in that everyone he 
touched turned to gold, as it was
being placed around their neck.
and, when you get done listening
to the level of disrespect
from one young ladyâ€™s punishing stories,
there are one hundred and thirty more
or so waiting in line on deck.
the glory came before these
heinous acts were largely brought to light,
and as i think of the violations of trust alone
i cannot stomach it with all of my might.

yet, those amazing ladies stood by each other
shoulder to shoulder,
hand holder, next to both young 
and older now,
having been one of the first,
collectively saying #metoo,
#nomore, and #timesup to twist the plot,
reversing the curse,
victims turned heroes,
who will never be for naught or forgot.

olympic doctor turned zero,
turned less than zero,
but nassar will not make a comeback
like junior downey.
and it seems abundantly clear heâ€™ll end up
somewhere, have no fear,
that is far darker than county,
with obscure astral entities surrounding
heart pounding, and torment confounding 
even the most light-hearted soul,
let alone his body of actionâ€™s collective toll
and what karma is mounting.

cheers to those who fought back tears
in their most impressionable 
and delicate years to perform feats
that would launch careers and 
steer the course of human history,
in spite of foreign jeers. cheers to those who
would inspire clear generations of peers
to face their fears and go for gold.
you are the reasons that otherâ€™s stories will be told.
you are the reasons why otherâ€™s stories will never need 
to be told.
you hold your fingers on the pulse of the nation.
you are the roses that grew from the wrought iron station.
you are the we who free other #victimsnomore
and help them cope,
you are the we who see the greater gift to be helping others
hold on to their hope.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
"panty portrait: kitty" from the panty project, 13 of 51
fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 19 x 14 inches .

the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
eliza hittmanâ€™s â€œbeach ratsâ€ is situated at the centre of an ongoing, opaque discourse about cinemaâ€™s turning towards a â€œfemale gazeâ€. it being a film by a woman about male homosexuality, one could maybe see abdellatif kechicheâ€™s â€œblue is the warmest colourâ€ as its cinematic inverse. is there a marked difference in how kechiche represents his leads and how hittman treats harris dickinson? in terms of the camera, i donâ€™t really think so. itâ€™s all just titillating objectification in the end. important to state is that i donâ€™t think that word should conjure up such unequivocally negative connotations; it is, i believe, an ineluctable fact of cinema as a medium. probably the only concrete difference we can discern pertains to the process of production; both exarchopoulos and seydoux stated that they felt violated and would not work with kechiche again. dickinson expressed no such qualms. maybe the female gaze just means less cannon fodder for #metoo, surely a worthy end in itself. 
in a way it feels reductive to talk about helene louvartâ€™s cinematography as if the most notable facet of it was her womanhood. the film is one of the most visually stunning works iâ€™ve seen in years; one feels as though it wouldnâ€™t suffer if you just turned the sound off (watch it while listening to a mix of the drums, denis sulta and debussy). dickinsonâ€™s performance is captivating, and if we can posit the existence of some distinctly female erotic impulse in the tender treatment of his body, then i can say sans qualms, hurrah for the female gaze. 
how and ever, despite its accomplishment, it canâ€™t help but feel like one film too many in a long, long (so fucking long) tradition of heteronormative â€œcoming-outâ€ stories. this narrative arc is a narrow one, with little to offer for gay people. iâ€™ll expand on these ideas tomorrow in my â€œgodâ€™s own countryâ€ review. suffice to say here that i am starved for silver-screen twink representation. someone, anyone, give me a movie about a messy bottom, a britney stan in the boilerhouse!
#beachrats #elizahittman

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
january is national slavery and human trafficking prevention month, culminating with national freedom day on february 1st and there are so many things that we can all do to help #abolish #slavery and #humantrafficking!
.
we all can help in small and large ways because the circumstances that might make any one of us vulnerable to human trafficking and #moderndayslavery is a coin toss of fate: who your parents are, where you are born, your age (because children only have the autonomy and rights that their parents choose to give them), your familyâ€™s socioeconomic status, how you look, your ability to work, your residency status, your gender, your race, your sexual orientation... the point is that any one of us could be vulnerable to trafficking depending upon what circumstances and family you are born into.
.
resources:
.
learn about the trajectory of human trafficking and how this happens at thelifestory.org (*trigger warning*)
.
to report a tip or ask for help for yourself or a friend, call the national human trafficking resource center at: 1-888-373-7888 or by texting help or info to befree (233733).
.
message me if you need any help finding resources.
.
things we can do to help:
volunteer with a local anti trafficking organization or with other organizations that help vulnerable populations such as homeless shelters, immigrant resource centers, transgender support groups, clinics, as a court advocate, domestic violence organizations and shelters.
.
there needs to be a more effective network of protections and resources to help rehabilitate victims of #trafficking. i was never removed from my father who trafficked me until i was 10 years old and i know that cps was called. cps alone is not enough.
.
thank you to the resilient people who are helping!

text:
the american psychological association has released new guidelines surrounding psychological practice with boys and men, and it focuses on how masculinity is experienced and performed. in a period of time where toxic masculinity is increasingly being discussed - both alongside and separately from movements like #metoo - i think this is hugely relevant and, quite frankly, about time. iâ€™ve thought about the impact of masculinity a bit as i helped my husband to navigate some of the pressures surrounding gender stereotyping and gender role strain, but admittedly, as a mother of three daughters, i havenâ€™t put as much thought as perhaps i should be into how the development of masculinity impacts boys and men. this document (which is easily google-able) can be a bit of heavy reading but i wanted to call your attention to it simply as itâ€™s very existence evidences just how important challenging traditional masculinity ideology is (you know, the â€˜anti-femininity - show no emotion, weakness, or fearâ€™ bullshit) if we are to enable our boys to grow up into well-balanced and psychologically developed men. here is a scary statistic, did you know that men are four times more likely than women to die of suicide? itâ€™s high time we started teaching our boys (all of our children) that it is ok not to be ok all of the time, and importantly, how to help themselves when they are feeling low or need support. iâ€™ve posted about some of these books before, but here are a few titles related to the subject of boys and masculinity: how to be a lion by ed vere, stories for boys who dare to be different by ben brooks, and how not to be a boy by richard webb.
.
what are your thoughts on this subject? do you have any other book suggestions that i can add to this list?

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
i can't believe i see grown women with daughters defending robert kelly's actions. what if that was your daughter or niece in that situation how would you feel then? be careful the heart your have towards others. yes it's true some may want to be there but there are others who are deceived, manipulated and mind controlled to stay did i mention some even abused emotionally, sexually and physically. being that i am a women who suffered from those things i take it very serious. enough is enough! empower and encourage one another that they are better than the little they settle for! that they are beautiful and no one should belittle them and make them feel any different! stop talking stupid and stand up! they are someone's child, someone's sister, someone's mother, someone's aunt and someone's friend!! oh not to mention the men... the men that defend him... it says a lot about you and your possible capabilities. 
#empowerwomen #standup #metoo #rkellyactionsaredangerous #enoughisenough

text:
if you think iâ€™m just upset about a film screening, think again. 
it sucks to be estranged from your father and live in the same house. it sucks to have to cover up how bad it really is between you two. it sucks to have been bullied for years. it sucks to be constantly pushed aside in favor of a disabled siblingâ€™s needs. it sucks to have constantly been bullied and treated like a freak for years. it sucks to have self-harmed and had to cover it up. it also sucks when several people tell you over and over again that you have talent and that they do feel touched and understood by the art you put out, but youâ€™re not getting the results you need on a much larger scale to prove them right. it sucks to have a bunch of #metoo stories. it sucks to come from a wildly successful family. it sucks to date someone who has a better career than you do. it sucks that i need to rely on people to come to my dumb little screenings to make me feel like my life has a modicum of meaning, but thatâ€™s the way it is (because i really donâ€™t). iâ€™m grateful to all the people who have showed up to my other screenings. but today was shit. i have others planned, and i donâ€™t even think i want to do them. iâ€™m just too humiliated right now.

iâ€™m posting this because iâ€™ve had people tell me before that theyâ€™re â€œamazedâ€ at what iâ€™m doing with my life and career, and while iâ€™m flattered, i would like to break that image before anyone goes around thinking thereâ€™s anything amazing about it. this is reality. this is being a nobody. this is people tiptoeing around your being a nobody by using euphemisms like â€œup-and-comingâ€ and â€œfledglingâ€. this the life of an artist.

oh, and a message to seventeen fellow armenians who said theyâ€™d be coming and didnâ€™t; before you cry about the world making us feel like weâ€™re nothing but a small group of people and that our contributions to society donâ€™t matter, maybe letâ€™s try making each otherâ€™s contributions to society feel like they matter? support eachother? just a thought. all iâ€™m saying is, i get much better viewership and praise from people not in my ethnic group. #armenians #film #themouseinthebread #artist s #bullshit

â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”
(for the feminists who will say, â€œ but if itâ€™s a man who rapes a woman, he shouldnâ€™t have any choice.â€ the answer is simple: 1.5% of all abortions are due to rape. having universal reproductive rights would affect the 98.5% that are not a result of rape. common sense also tells you that with the universal reproductive rights, rapists will in no way receive rights over the child.)

text_retweet:
i just listened to this segment today and this piece struck a cord with me. i definitely recommend checking out the full interview.

sway: "what do you think about some of the women who have been outside of r kelly concerts saying things like, "take me hostage"? what is that?" iyanla vanzant: "it's the collective sickness that we have because we've forgotten who we are and we haven't assimilated fully into a society, a culture that diminishes, demeans, and dismisses us. so one of the easiest ways to assert your power, to feel your power, is sex. sex is a power source. so when you feel powerless. look at the number of people who live in poverty, unemployed, haven't reached their vision or their quest in life, but they got 8 kids. why? because sex is powerful so they're looking for a way to be powerful, feel power, exchange power and sex is the way to do it. simply because we haven't been taught who we are." wow! #foodforthought #sexispower #sexispowerful #sacredenergyexchange #believesurvivors #metoo #sexualassault #rape #sexualabuse #sexaddiction #trauma  #repost from @realsway : "very interesting conversation today with @iyanlavanzant. congratulations on her new season of #fixmylife @owntv airing 1/12. we talked about the #survivingrkelly documentary but she calls out his inner circle and more importantly highlights that this is a much bigger issue in our country than just r. kelly.

text:
@annelisaleinbach : i began this residency in the midst of a wave of controversies about sexual assault in my home country of the us. with these thoughts on my mind and the nature around me, i was reminded of the ancient greek myth of daphne and apollo: the god apollo is consumed with lust for the mortal daphne, but she rejects his advances. he chases her, and as she flees she prays to the gods for salvation. just as apollo is about to grab her, she is turned into a tree - saved from his grasp, but immobilized forever as he walks away unharmed. how could these ancient themes be interpreted in today's world? i began a series of paintings exploring this myth, incorporating my sketches of the trees and plants in portugal. swipe to see the process!
.
.
.

#metoo #domesticviolence messiah @louisfarrakhan teaches "there are things in our lives that have been done to us. from the time we were babies, a word from a mother that wasn't thinking; a father that didn't care; a teacher that was off the mark who, when they said things, whose words became â€œcommandsâ€ to you. 
and these commands are in your head, stored in the subconscious mind. 
any woman who has been â€ªmolestedâ€¬, who has been â€ªrapedâ€¬ by a father, by an uncle, by a friend, by a relative: college doesn't free you; church doesn't free you from that pain. it gives you an emotional escape. but to relieve you, and give you a chance to live â€¦ see, the scientologists call this process â€ªauditing â€¬. but we who are muslims, we who are scriptural people, we don't use the term engrams. in theology, we call it the exorcising of demons.

and so, when you're being audited, they just ask you to go back. 
every one of us has a file in our head, and the auditor will take you back to a moment of pain  which is something that people did to you, not so much what you did to others.

when you look at our behavior, you're looking at â€œdemonsâ€ that are sitting up inside of us that have to come out in order for us to be what god intends for us to be. 
and that means that every one of us have to be purified! 
all of us!"@louisfarrakhan: preparation of the mind

text:
poetry slam has been around in dakar, senegal for quite some time.Â  in 2008, i transitioned into the slamming community after displaying my lyrical talents on the streets of dakar during the hip hop movement.Â  i found a new manner to deliver my message in an environment that permitted better control of the ambiance within a room so that the audience could really engage and hear well to identify and reflect on the issues in which i found toÂ  be most pressing for us to be aware and focus on in our society today.Â  i tend to focus on well being, religion, and political issues and agendas.Â  but in this space one can focus on science, education, and social issues such as the #metoo movement, etc

text:
i noticed i have a ton of new followers, so i wanted to re-introduce myself.

my name is melissa, i am a #thrivingsurvivor of childhood sexual abuse & domestic violence #wife to my ğŸ’— & a #motherofsons as well as a health & wellness mentor & advocate. i believe you should #lovelife & you have the power to do so. it is my mission to support survivors, walk along side them on their healing journey & assist them towards strengthening themselves in every area of their lives.

you are not alone. to every little girl that has been molested, sexually assaulted or abused. to every teen & woman that has survived domestic violence & endured the same fate.
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
i have too.
yes, #metoo
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
i was 6 years old when i was molested at the hands of a stranger as i attempted to ride my bicycle down the street one day.
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
i never got that far, i barely left my drive way when a brazen beast robbed me of my innocence, purity & security.
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
it happened again sometime later one night at the grocery store with my mother. i was about a 1/2 aisle length behind her pushing the shopping cart when a man touched me. i remember leaving the cart & running to my mother screaming â€œhe touched me, that man touched meâ€
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
i only remember bits & pieces of what happened after that. maybe due to suppressing it for so long, itâ€™s the only way my young mind knew to cope & for  self preservation.
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
i publicly shared my story on ig on 10/17/17 for the 1st time in almost 30 years. for all those years i was suffocating from keeping it tucked away in the depths of my soul for so long.
ğŸ–¤
the only way to be free & begin the healing process at my core was to stand in my truth. own my story & share it with the world in hopes of helping another woman or child that has stood in my shoes.
â–ªï¸â–ªï¸â–ªï¸
to all the little girls that have grown into women with scars seared on her heart. iâ€™m living proof & a testimony that there is freedom & healing on the other side of the pain you hold in your heart. itâ€™s time to #loveyourlife
ğŸ–¤

text:
#metoo  #timesup #muterkellyÂ  #godsaystimesupÂ  my next book, "the me too movement of the bible."Â understanding the will of god through the word of god and the me too movement

i had great hesitation in writing a book about the me too movement and the bible. in my hesitation i begin to think that maybe a woman should write this book. in this book i would be challenged to write about things that most preachers never preach or teach in their bible lessons. the sunday school lessons that are written never deal with the issue of sexual assault. most books that are written in the christian arena never deal with the issues that will be discussed in this book. i am about to write about something that if i came across in a movie, i would turn the movie off because i do not find such matters entertaining even in the world of make-believe movies.

but in dealing with these kinds of issues in real life you can't turn it off. you can't fast forward through the scenes that you don't like in real life. many who will read this book wish they could turn it off or fast forward through the pain. this book is a book written for all the silent victims of sexual harassment and sexual assault.Â  i pray that god will use this book to heal all the hurt and the shame that surrounds these heinous crimes.

coming spring 2019

psa #metoo 
i knew that if i came forward publicly to tell the truth about me being sexually assaulted in the workplace at my job at the university of illinois, ceasefire/cure violence that people would try to discredit me. but i refused to keep quiet.
i refused to go away. i will not be broken. 
i knew i would become a victim of character assassination. 
well there is a rumor being circulated in the communities in chicago that i am a 'white supremacist racist'. this is an outrage.this is an effort to make me back down from the truth and to silence me.
i will not be silenced! i will stand strong for women everywhere! ~angalia bianca 
#stopsexabuse #speakout #uic #ceasefire #cureviolence #enoughisenough #feminist #sexabuse #sexualabuse #sexualharassment #metoo

text:
binge eating and smoking linked to bullying and abuse

study reports people who experience bullying or abuse (sexual or otherwise) have a lower quality of life comparable to those living with chronic health conditions, such as diabetes or depression. 
the study also reports those who are abused are more likely to develop harmful behaviors such as smoking or binge eating.

my commentary:  these findings do not distinguish unresolved versus resolved trauma. resolutuon can be achieved through various types of therapeutic modalities and makes a person more resilient and compassionate (better) than before. what doesn't kill you ..... https://neurosciencenews.com/smoking-binge-eating-abuse-10512

justin groode md | founder of pathway formulas llc

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
it's so beautiful this morning! 
went to yoga and then bought some new clothes @athleta and then heading to @noirlashstudio 
it's so wonderful to be debt free and able to splurge on these luxuries with no regrets 
financial stress is so powerful and i never really thought it was something that impacted me that much but the freedom of paying in cash helps me stay in the present moment and not mindlessly purchase things and deal with the credit card bill later. 
when i left treatment i had debt and wanted to be free from it so i used @daveramsey financial peace university classes a few months after getting home and it helped enormously in getting focused and now i am living my best life!

not spending money on alcohol was critical for me as it lead to overeating and overspending. without alcohol i never need to order late night pizza or miss workouts i paid for ğŸ•. if you haven't tried sobriety to help with debt and weight loss perhaps it is a new and different approach to these constant issues that we seem to cycle in and out of for years. 
#debtfreecommunity #sober #weightlossjourney #debtfree #soberissexy #soberyogi #transformation #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
while few respondents believe the #metoo movement has changed their workplace, we do have an opportunity to effect change on campus.

cynthia j. wood presents her brand-new training course, "speak up & speak out about sexual harassment: find your assertive voice." cynthia serves as the national operations coordinator for feminists for life of america. prior to ffl, she worked for the federal government for 35 years as a trainer for numerous workshops, including prevention of sexual harassment (posh), effective communication, and team-building and leadership workshops. cynthia received a law degree from university of houston law center in 1999. she has been a bar member of the d.c. court of appeals, virginia, and florida. she is married and has four children.

contact us at info@feministsforlife.org to schedule her to speak at your school or organization. source article, https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/americans-say-metoo-movement-hasnt-impacted-workplace-1174159?

text:
am i asking for it?

this evening, i got sexually assaulted. again. in my train home, some foreign men, speaking a foreign language, tried to squeeze next to me on my seat, wouldn't let me go to the train doors to get out at my stop, and finally drove me into a corner to grab my ass several times, to eventually place a hand fully between my legs.
this all happened in an almost emtpy @ns_online train from eindhoven to maarheeze. 
it's sick how my uncomfortableness is entertainment to some. this isn't something i'd usually post on this account, but it needs to come to people's attention that these things do still happen.

#metoo #metoomovement #sexualassault #assault #assaulted #amiaskingforit #treinleven #ns_online #aanranding #indetrein

text:
a new name.

an oft-impaled heart is overlooked, hidden by surface smiles and "okays." years ago, when the still-beating organ was going through amputations, it screamed. no-one heard as ghoul-esque audiences were otherwise engaged in acts of subversive torture. as blood created a slowly, meandering trail, the wound gathered a thickened scab cloak over herself. representation of the heart then faced the world, while the wound saw no-thing but her own broken reflection. 
through dozens of moons, "okays" drifted from the lips as cracks broadened in the scab cloak...age wrinkles that naturally find exact moments to shriek. 
then one ugly day the wound intended the cloak's obliteration, or at least thought she did. as it happened, the magic spell only hoped to convey the end of hiding, it did not carry the wound to a full reveal. 
dozens more moons, and hundreds of "okays" passed before the wound finally turned inside-out to scream, the sound now the only thing she sees. until it isn't. when that day arrives the wound will choose a new name.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

pieces from my new collection sensual floral images... inspired, in part, by the work of robert mapplethorpe.  next month, eight of these pieces will be displayed in a gallery in newberg, along with other members from photo club pdx. "sex is mysterious, often sublimely so. sex can open us to ridicule, or to enlightenment. nothing about sex is for sure, except that it's consequential. - robert w. fuller ph.d.

this project began innocently enough as i was exploring heavy, supple baskets of fragrant and exotic flowers, wet and dripping on my front porch after their nightly watering, while i was experimenting with unconventional light sources and angles. it wasnâ€™t until later, as i was processing the images, that i realized how the flora often resembled genitalia. it wasnâ€™t long before all i could see were sexual attributes in all of my floral images.

sexually is the pinnacle of taboo topics, while it is also the most pervasive force in nature and in human behavior. sexually is everywhere. we see it, feel it, fear it, desire it, make decisions based upon it every day.  to be human is to be sexual, and to be sexual is to be human.

while there is a wonderful, healthy, pleasurable aspect to our sexually, there is also a darker, disturbing, violent, and damaging facet as well. the recent #metoo movement can be argued by some, to be an example of the consequences wrought upon society when our sexually, as a human condition, is ignored and shamed. 
my hope is that these images will bring thoughts of sexually to the forefront of the viewerâ€™s mind, endeavoring to normalize a topic that continues to be awkward and forbidden even in our more modern and liberal society." #metoo #robertmapplethorpe #sex #sensual #personalproject2018 #pcpdx #womanphotographer #tryingsomethingnew #mysterious #robertwfullerphd #uniqueperspective #beautyeverywhere #clickinmoms #clickmagazine #f #flowers #flora #clematis #purple #suggestive #beautiful #noshame

text:
i have learned a lot since i started my healing process. i think the most important lesson i have learned is that it is okay to not be okay. it is okay to need a break, and it is okay to take a break. healing from abuse and rape does not happen over night. it takes years. i will be spending the rest of my life healing from what i have been through, and that's okay. 
taking a break does not make you lazy. it does not make you irresponsible. it does not make you selfish. it is simply you showing yourself the love you deserve from yourself. it's okay to ask for help. it's okay to get help. support, therapy, medication, anything you need, it's okay. taking care of yourself is important. 
i used to believe these lies. i would overload myself with unnecessary weight because i thought it was selfish to take time for myself. i would believe admitting that i'm not okay or taking breaks would mean i was weak, irresponsible, and lazy.

it took me a while, but i have finally started to realize that the opinions of others do not matter, even if they are family or friends. they are not the ones feeling the pain. they are not the ones dealing with the aftermath. they're not dealing with the nightmares and panic attacks or the depression that comes along with it. so i will not apologize for helping myself. it may have taken me months to realize, but it is okay to not be okay. 
i know there are so many people dealing with the same issues. please remember that your healing is important. taking care of yourself is important, no matter what anyone tells you. it doesn't matter what was done to you, you still matter. and if you don't have a support system, or you're unsure where to begin helping yourself, i'm always here. â¤ï¸
â€¢
â€¢

this is huge and important and yes.
-
repost from @theconsciouskid

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning: â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.
-
the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€
-
the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.
-
the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others; and reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide."
-
apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews
-

repost from @theconsciouskid using @repostregramapp - "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
here are 5 things you need to know about me:
1.) i am a hopeless overachiever. i set goals and hit them and then what? in 2019 i am changing my mindset to be a gracious and intentional achiever. 
2.) i had a miscarriage and it changed me for the better. it made me realize how precious life is and that you should always count your blessings.
3.) i knew i was going to marry my husband after our first date and blurted our that i loved him way way too early on in the relationship. what can i say, when you know, you know! 
4.) wellness is ingrained in my soul and teaching people how to be well is my passion. i have a bs in biology and currently work at a healthcare company in oncology analytics. 
5.) #metoo, #metoo, #metoo. (thatâ€™s not a typo). but i donâ€™t let it define me anymore. i once cared way to much how others perceived me but i have since let go of caring about others opinions and instead accepted who i am, flaws/strengths and all. 
i only have a few close girlfriends and am not used compliments or having someone (other than family and my close friends) lift me up and sincerely congratulate me for my achievements. i have finally found my tribe and i am stepping out of my comfort zone like crazy. from shy and emotionally damaged to unapologetically me!! if you get me, join me. show me the ğŸ”¥and join me on this incredible journey. â€¢

celebrating steps toward liberating us all from toxic masculinity. fyi: this is the same association that in 1952 deemed homosexuality as a "mental disorder". this... this is progress! 
from @theconsciouskid: "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
:
in this photograph from 2004, convicted sex offender jeffrey epstein speaks with then-harvard professor alan dershowitz, who would later serve on epsteinâ€™s defense team. rick friedman/corbis via getty images
jeffrey epstein could have gone to prison for life.

the money manager was accused of sexually abusing dozens of underage girls at his palm beach mansion between 2001 and 2006. but as julie k. brown reports at the miami herald, he ultimately got just 13 months in a county jail, thanks to a deal signed by alexander acosta, then the us attorney for miami and now president trumpâ€™s secretary of labor. on tuesday, epstein settled a lawsuit in which some of his accusers were expected to testify, avoiding yet again the prospect of facing the women in court.

epstein has said that any encounters he had with his accusers were consensual, and that he believed they were 18 at the time.

the story of how epstein got such a light sentence â€” and who was involved â€” is a master class in the power dynamics that have been exposed by the #metoo movement but have yet to truly change.
when authorities began investigating epstein, he assembled a team of private investigators to dig up dirt on the girls who accused him and the police and prosecutors working the case. then he and his team of powerful lawyers â€” including alan dershowitz and kenneth starr â€” were able to convince prosecutors to go easy on him despite disturbing allegations by a growing number of women and girls. (according to axios, dershowitz is still advising epstein, saying, â€œhe has called me a couple of times about legal issues, because iâ€™m still technically his lawyer.â€) epstein was proud of his â€œcollectionâ€ of famous friends, which included bill clinton and donald trump, and thereâ€™s long been speculation that some of these friends may have participated in his abuses. but because he has been able to avoid harsh punishment and minimize publicity around the details of his case, heâ€™s also been able to keep details about anyone else who may have been involved out of the public eye.

text: found the print for the image i discussed, in a previous post, about having ann from ford, or mode, david wilkenfeldâ€™s agency, interested when i first started modeling, many moons ago...and choosing the smaller, to get what i thought might be more attention for my career pursuit, as suggested by others who i thought knew more as photographers, etc. mode later closed, so it was not the best choice and was a lesson learned, though david is a nice man...and the ironic thing was, at my broadcaster brotherâ€™s funeral, the station director, was related to donna sexton, who lived with eileen ford and was a top model from the 80s and was one of the main reasons i got going, because he suggested i model and told her about me, then she gave good advice and encouragement feeling i should have gone far. neat! so really appreciate fordâ€™s reputation for caring about their models, wish i chose that path, and value the great people who encouraged me, in the beginning, so i could leave the complacent persons that would have been content for me to go nowhere fast at that time! the one thing i regret is being forced to decide between an offer to pay for me to go to school for combustion engineering, by an employer at the time, and thinking i would be stuck in a cubicle for the rest if my life, and the feast or famine world of fashion, of which i was not savvy enough to know was going to bevup and down per earnings. now that girls donâ€™t have as much pressure to only model when they are young, i would have chosen to take that offer and then go model!...but that was the climate at the time and times have changed! text:
as we move into our  me too berks: a time to healâ€”empowering all people-marketing efforts (as in, please spread the word on the amazing 5 weeks of free informative events that truly help people this spring), i am finding myself in a regular internal dialogue about what it means to actually be â€œempoweredâ€ and what is the role of â€œpersonal boundariesâ€ in this empowerment? 
one example from the last decade that stands out as such a contrast to my teens and early adulthood is ecstatic dance/free movement: 
unlike my early years dancing in night clubs and bars in the cities i livedâ€”miami, atlanta and nycâ€”today, in ecstatic dance/free-form space, i move without the fear of someone trying to touch me who i have not invited. i move without fear of being objectified. i move without fear of being judged for not being a trained dancer of any kind. i move because i am. because i belong on this earth and i have a right to enjoy my body. 
in our @homepym ecstatic dances,  i allow my body to be the instrument in which the music plays, joining in on the collective discovering of joy,  humanity and a deep welling up of our primal expression of this-is-me-right-here-right-now-ness. 
so, my friends, what are the practices you do that both empower and honor your personal boundaries? please share. this @metooberks movement is about healing (not shaming). your thoughts matter!

text:
these sessions are absolutely beneficial. today, as actors and as individuals in life, we took time to know the difference between permission and consent. //////////////////////////////////////////////////////
from @sircajdar â˜®ï¸ itâ€™s words like these, from cityrep (oklahoma city repertory theatre) artistic director donald jordan, that make me supremely proud and gratefully honored to lead the consent & intimacy workshops for their upcoming production of hair. read them with the weight it deserves: â€œat cityrep, our company was shocked by the revelations that came to light with the courageous #metoo movement.

having become aware of the kind of abuse that was going on in so many other places, we were determined that our theatre would be a place that not only prohibits such disrespectful behavior, but one that actively works to counteract it.

we have always striven to foster a safe, respectful, warm and caring creative environment, which we feel is most conducive to making great theatre.

now we have further redoubled our efforts, incorporating the the pillars: a guideline for approaching scenes of intimacy created by intimacy directors international, the chicago theatres "not in our house" concepts, and the foundational principles of actors equity association, which are at the heart of our theatre's ideals. 
it is my hope that each artist who is introduced to these ideas will carry forth throughout their careers, introducing and encouraging them as the standard for theatre makers.â€ ğŸŒ for more info on â€œcreating safe places for dangerous workâ€ or training opportunities in the field of intimacy for stage and film, visit intimacy directors international at teamidi.org!

#intimacyeverywhere
#wintimacy
#consentculture
#teamidi

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
lord, use my story for your glory!  i will continue to use my voice every opportunity i get. my story of survival will be someone else's saving grace. 
sharing your story is not an easy thing to do but the best feeling in the world is knowing that you're helping others heal through the transparency in your testimony. never judge a book by its cover,  you never know the pain that a person has had to endure. this is a season where people are in need of being surrounded by love pressure,  there is enough pain in the world and the enemy is looking for who he can devour. be a solution to the problem not salt to wounds. check the spirit you are operating from and begin on your own healing so god can get the full glory.

god placed it in my heart early last year (2017) to write my book "my costa rican humming bird sings breaking the bondage and answering the call" (currently available on amazon) for such a time as this. depression, isolation and suicidal thoughts are a real thing in all nationalities and ethnic backgrounds.  it is time to take the shame off of these topics and begin addressing the monster currently affecting our nation today. 
it is an honor to serve as ambassador for naasca. abuse cycles, depression and mental health are real issues that need to be addressed and supported.

here is my interview where i shared my real story about my sexual abuse on naasca:

http://www.blogtalkradio.com/naasca/2018/10/18/stop-child-abuse-now-scan--1988

no weapon that is formed against thee shall prosper; and every tongueÂ thatÂ shall rise against thee in judgment thou shalt condemn. thisÂ isÂ the heritage of the servants of the lord, and their righteousnessÂ isÂ of me, saith the lord.

job 23:10 "but he knows where i am going. and when he tests me, i will come out as pure as gold.

text:
i deeply thank priya malik to come up with "mr.player" as i desperately wanted to write on this one after i could hardly see 15 minutes of the koffee with karan last week and trust me i have never wasted time of my life like this ever in my life before.
(this includes me reading half girlfriend btw)
dear pandya, year after year the term "dignified woman" and "classy gentleman" is losing its meaning by mere visuals about how they look rather than how they act.
there is nothing classy or cool as your clothes, in saying,
i would just see their moves rather asking those girls their names.
i pity you today.
not because this "koffee" was the costliest coffee of your life,
i pity you for "main aaj karke aya" didn't get any tight slap by your parents at right time.
i am sure you must be the "mera raja beta sabse pyaara" as you are so talented and brought pride to the family and country,
but every woman seeing you talk cringed at every second trust me.
yours "karke aya" is not a problem for us
as it's your life, your girls, your parents
but the body language and the tone you spoke with, shows how male chauvinist you are and see woman just as an object.
coz my dear even if you are gentleman in love (which you are not, but suppose) or a casanova,
you don't go declaring your last night to the nation.
i now know talent has nothing to do with values after the #metoo movement,
but we don't respect dravid and sachin for enormous talent on field but what they are off-field as a man.
the consistency in keeping the dignity and fame for so many years need great discipline and you surely lack in that department.
you being a public figure is a privilege.
youth look upto you
the respect and fame comes with great responsibility.
the most ridiculous part was your apology,
coz i didn't become this woman who knows what is sexist or what is not in a day,
and so my dear,
your words were not invented in a day but it shows this is what you are.
by the way, on youtube there are old fun interviews of dignified cricketers for detoxification if you need.
.
.
.

text:
running into 2019. crushing my goals. the little person greeting me at the finish line of my 2nd half marathon is my daughter. during the run in moments when i wanted to stop, take a break or quit i thought about my husband, daughter and son who were waiting to cheer my on at the finish line. the love for them pushed me through. the mama bear inside of me kept motivating me to show my babies that you can accomplish anything that you work and dream of â¤ï¸
.
.
i was over 200 pounds 12 years ago and would talk about my dream of running a half marathon. people would laugh at me and it seemed so far fetched at the time. i was determined to make all of my dreams and goals come true once i became sober. i was given a second chance at life, i am meant to do more then suffer in addiction. i am more then a trauma survivor today, more then an addict, more then the horrible person that i thought i was.  i became filled with love, passion and ambition like no other. i began to love myself. .
.
.
i have new goals now that all of my original ones have been accomplished.  my healing and helping others has taken on a whole new purpose. iâ€™m here to love, support and guide others on their path. ğŸ¥°
.
.
what drives you? what are your goals? are you ready to take like to the next level? 
are you ready for healing and abundance? ğŸ˜Š

tweet_full:
running into 2019. crushing my goals. the little person greeting me at the finish line of my 2nd half marathon is my daughter. during the run in moments when i wanted to stop, take a break or quit i thought about my husband, daughter and son who were waiting to cheer my on at the finish line. the love for them pushed me through. the mama bear inside of me kept motivating me to show my babies that you can accomplish anything that you work and dream of â¤ï¸
.
.
i was over 200 pounds 12 years ago and would talk about my dream of running a half marathon. people would laugh at me and it seemed so far fetched at the time. i was determined to make all of my dreams and goals come true once i became sober. i was given a second chance at life, i am meant to do more then suffer in addiction. i am more then a trauma survivor today, more then an addict, more then the horrible person that i thought i was.  i became filled with love, passion and ambition like no other. i began to love myself. .
.
.
i have new goals now that all of my original ones have been accomplished.  my healing and helping others has taken on a whole new purpose. iâ€™m here to love, support and guide others on their path. ğŸ¥°

text:
prevention of sexual harassment at workplace gets a fillipÂ in hyderabadâ€™s it hub

hyderabadâ€™s it industry is taking the lead and gearing up to train its internal complaints committee (icc) to tackle newer, subtler ways of sexual harassment that are surfacing everyday
what constitutes sexual harassment and how to tackle complaints of harassment at work place? in the #metoo era, answers to these questions, while imminent, are more often than not, missing from common knowledge. hyderabadâ€™s it industry is taking the lead and gearing up to train its internal complaints committee (icc) to tackle newer, subtler ways of sexual harassment that are surfacing everyday.
sexual harassment in it companies can be very nuanced and just based on body language and codes which can vary from company to company,â€ noted varsha bhargavi, a gender sensitization trainer. from the nuances of the posh (prevention of sexual harassment at workplace) law to workshops on gender sensitisation is part of these initiatives. â€œthe icc falls short in reporting of incidents and implementation of the act. the whole gender sensitisation comes in when we try to improve this, wherein people can say what is and what is not harassment and report and identify better,â€ added varsha. the hysea (hyderabad software enterprises association) plans on equipping its 300-member team for tackling complaints of harassment adeptly.

a session was already held in january first week and two more are scheduled. even a government body like she teams is pushing the narrative of safer workspace by organising a first of its kind work s h o p c a l l e d sh(out)- sexual harassment out, they are planning on a 24-month workshop cycle to cover various industries by sensitising them â€” right from the ceo to the heads of management. many of these workshops are also focusing beyond the lens of sexual harassment and discussing about the inherent patriarchy and misogyny in both men and women.

concept of consent and workspace romances are also becoming a common point in the discussion. sources say that icc members of various tech companies are also looking at a more channelised system for redressal of cases.

text:
i just finished watched the docuseries @survivingrkellytv and i feel embarassed. embarassed that as a young adult , when the allegations came out against him, i never thought critically about them, but instead laughed at the dave chappelle skit poking fun at it. when allegations as severe as pedophilia and child pronography come out, it should never be taken lightly. victims should never have to feel ashamed, their predators should. 
as a mother this shit scares the crap out of me. it's hard as a parent to know where, when and how to start the conversation surrounding body awareness and boundaries with our children, but it's crucial. we have started the conversation in our household, with calling body parts by their actual name, from birth, and to now discussing boundaries. the boundaries conversation came up one day when i was bathing both of the boys. lazio reached over and touched luciano's penis and then looked down at his own. i did not yell. i did not get mad. children are curious in nature. instead, i used this as an opportunity to talk about boundaries and body awareness. i think as parents it is our duty to educate our children and start the conversation. remember you are setting the stage for open and honest dialogue for years to come.
