text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
your *daughters and sons and and sisters and brothers and nieces and nephews* will hear you defending a *sex offender and thatâ€™s why they wonâ€™t tell you that *somebody is touching them *or has raped them. 
less than approx. 3% of all sexual assault cases anywhere that empirical data is gathered are false allegations. and many of those are at nameless people.

some peopleâ€”idiotsâ€”hear of a handful of sexual assault cases on the news and think â€œmen are being attacked!â€ â€œreputations are being ruined.â€ when, in reality, lives of victims are being ruined, and thatâ€™s what people should be outraged about.

imagine being such a piece of shit that youâ€™ve spent more time and energy in your life defending sex offenders than you ever have standing up for victims?

iâ€™ve heard people ask: â€œwhy do people wait so long to speak up?â€ all the while, never actually using this wonderful tool called the internet to access the abundance of information which can inform them of the myriad of reasons why, with â€œnot being believedâ€ included. itâ€™s literally their choice to remain ignorant. 
some reason include shame (to themselves and their family), guilt (yes, victims often blame themselves), fear of repercussions (to themselves, to the family, to the perpetrator), cultural pressure that these things remain within the family, trauma which tries to suppress it which prevents the person from having to relive it, and the list goes on. 
the sheer ignorance and arrogance of people who have the blessing to have never been sexually assaulted, free from the trauma and pain it causes, using their narrow mindsets to try and rationalize the experiences of those who have experienced it astounds me.

these people, instead of being quick to judge and criticize and dismiss these people whom it took a lot of bravery to finally speak up, need to go educate themselves and/or support the victims, or just shut up and get back in their own lane. if one wants to take the stance that the accused are innocent until proven guilty, then donâ€™t defend the accused nor attack the victims. just be quiet. #sexualassault #victimadvocacy #victims #metoo #ibelieveyou

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
i met someone on here who reached out for help.  she didnâ€™t know me and is still scared to talk on the phone but she relies on me to help her through the hard times.  yesterday she spent the day with her son and celebrated 4 months in recovery.  without a doubt in my mind i know god pig her in my life for a reason. 
abuse is so manipulative.  on december 20th of last year she got on a plane and left her son and family to go be with her abuser.  trauma and abuse change the way your brain works.  the closest thing i can compare narcissistic abuse to is like an addiction you just canâ€™t quit.

she stopped talking to me and i figured she just found a sponsor in her home town and didnâ€™t want to talk anymore.  well a little over a week ago she reached out to me and told me where she really was and that she didnâ€™t know what to do.

her mom bought her a plane ticked home but the problem was, she could have made many mistakes and not made it on that plane. for about 2-3 days i have her advice on how to get out of her situation without him finding out.  i was terrified she wasnâ€™t going to get on the plane.  she is back with her son today.

god brought her into my life by asking one simple question.  does anyone want to talk about spirituality? 
so today iâ€™m going to ask, does anyone want to talk about god, maybe your having a hard time finding a higher power, or you just want to talk about recovery, life, tell me a joke! dm me!  i promise to get my blog up and running one of these days! 
oh and i love you beautiful young lady that reached out to me and was vulnerable! ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼âœŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ğŸ¼

text:
through the narrow gate by karen armstrong

karen armstrong shares her real life story about becomming a nun in london during the 60's and her ultimate decision to renounce her vows; leaving the convent before the revolution of the second vatican.

her experiences as a postulant and a novice can only be described as emotionally, spiritually, and even physically abusive. the eerie part is that it's so subtle and manipulative, it's understandable how so many women wouldn't even realize it was happening to them; especially considering a lot of the abuse was disguised under devotion to god.

karen's story is an act of bravery. she joins the sea of voices speaking out about the abuses they have experienced in their homes, religions, public spaces, institutions, and workplaces. their words creating tidal waves of turmoil as we navigate how to better support victims and demand justice reformation.

this is how change happens. as uncomfortable as we feel hearing these stories and the amount of work we have to put in to change the ways of our societies, this is the only way to protect our future generations from the suffering so commonly endured and kept secret.

#30books #30books2019 #bookreview #iread #karenarmstrong #nun #catholic #religion #god #secondvaticancouncil #reformation #abuse #metoo #timesup #speakout #brave

her experiences as a postulant and a novice can only be described as emotionally, spiritually, and even physically abusive. the eerie part is that it is so subtle and manipulative, it is understandable how so many women would not even realize it was happening to them; especially considering a lot of the abuse was disguised under devotion to god.

karen's story is an act of bravery. she joins the sea of voices speaking out about the abuses they have experienced in their homes, religions, public spaces, institutions, and workplaces. their words creating tidal waves of turmoil as we navigate how to better support victims and demand justice reformation.

this is how change happens. as uncomfortable as we feel hearing these stories and the amount of work we have to put in to change the ways of our societies, this is the only way to protect our future generations from the suffering so commonly endured and kept secret.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: east coast. yeah there's been some moments, although you know i'd not change a thing except the system itself. i've developed an unhealthy coping mechanism. it's kinda everywhere, and i can't stop. regardless, what's happening is internally looking for comfort externally, and not in a comparative competitive way, you all remind me of people i care about. everywhere, everyday. outside of all reasons to argue, one the main reasons i argue is seeing people i know and love in others and not being able to see them,  and not seeing the human i'm speaking with directly for who they are, and having to push back just enough to get to know them for them. otherwise i'm not being fair, to the new human potential friend. human enough to recognise the personalities, features, of one or multiple loved ones as they are to exist, in a person i've never met. at first i thought it was a sick joke. know my anger and many stealth like escape modes, wasn't my best moment. also, i feel it is impossible to sneak now. adjusting, yet kinda....about it, lost the sneak ability, can we atleast let me think i'm hiding. it's beautiful, how we all are so different and the same, earthlings, stardustians, not certain if i started doing this out of any reason other than looking for the good in meeting others, it's not fair to the new people to stand there and immediately feel like hey, you've got a lot there. i see you as many people or one specific that mean something to me, and it makes me want to tell you, you mean something to me. it's great, yet i just don't know you or  intentions and that could be dangerous to start allowing that to be how i get to know others. we've been friends over 10 years now, not worried about your weird side burns, and how i think youre great, yet who is reflecting, when i dont know you well. the system, certain jobs, places, i have to leave, if you expect me to check the people i care about at the door. i won't, we go places, jobs, school, ect. to better our lives, that's not success or purpose if losing someone is expected to perform a task. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #humanity

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
top tip 4 for building diversity and inclusion: build a strategy

implementing a diversity and inclusion strategy can seem overwhelming â€“ after all, weâ€™re talking about creating a workplace that is inclusive for all â€“ so keep things simple and start small.
your recruitment process is a good starting block; from the writing of job descriptions and the screening questions to the interview process and offer of employment, what attributes and qualities are you valuing in candidates? are you recruiting like for like or are you looking for individuals who complement the team by filling gaps in approach and skill sets?

text:
what made my presentation to cfuw st. catharines this past week extra special was my mom reading my speaker's bio and introducing me to the group of 100 women! as a 20+ year member of cfuw and past president, she has contributed hours and hours of her time and energy to the niagara community, and as well has well been the listening ear to my what-ifs and what-nexts over the past many, many years.

thank you to president gail neff for your warm welcome and these thoughtful words in feedback to my talk on creating cultures of care and how to support survivors of sexual abuse.
â€¢
"as daughters, mothers, grandmothers, current and former teachers and professional women, and active volunteers in our community, your advice to be sensitive, non-judgemental listeners, supporters, and believers to family and friends resonated with us all.  in my many years of attending monthly meetings, i have never seen the enthusiastic, spontaneous, standing ovation you received after your presentation.  thank you, laura, for what you do." - gail neff, president, cfuw st. catharines
â€¢

text:
i forgive the stranger that brutally raped and beat me nearly ten years ago. the man that haunted me from behind metal bars as he served a 60 year sentence. the man that put me in the hospital, with emotional and physical wounds to last a lifetime. the man that dragged me through a two-year court and trial process of retraumatization and an attempted character assasination.
â€¢
i know itâ€™s hard for some people to understand how i could forgive a â€œcold-blooded monster." but the truth is, i use to be a monster myself. many people donâ€™t know that a short while after my attack, i ended up behind those same metal bars. my pain had turned to anger and boiled over into blind rage and hatred for the world around meâ€”a violent combination i drunkenly took out on two police offers who were just trying to do their job.
â€¢
i realized in that jail cell that by holding onto my hatred, i was still his hostage. i was tired of feeling shackled to him, shackled to the personal anger that he forced upon me, that i then internalized and spread into the world. it was a cycle of hatred i wanted to end. so instead i chose forgiveness. and rather than being blind with rage, the forgiveness allowed me to see him with eyes of compassion and empathy.
â€¢
i reflected back on the childhood stories of suffering that his lawyers illustrated as they pleaded his case. he was orphaned at the age of 8, was raised by a single aunt as 1 of 10 children, had poor schooling and mental & physical health conditions. it all made sense. you see he had allowed his pain to make him bitter, full of hatred and violent. but i could make a different choice. so instead i allowed my pain to make me better, softer & more loving.
â€¢
i choose empathy & forgiveness because god intended for me to be free. it doesnâ€™t excuse what he did. it doesnâ€™t mean heâ€™s absolved from the punishment heâ€™s serving.
â€¢
iâ€™ve contemplated over the years going to visit him in prison. what would he think? what would i say? ultimately, i wish that heâ€™d see that despite how shitty this world can be, thereâ€™s still hope that we can come out better on the other side. who knows, maybe thereâ€™s hope for him too. just maybe, he can be redeemed.

text: it took me longer than i wanted to get this out because it took me time to get through surviving r kelly. it was hard to watch. i encourage you to watch it. i lived in miami when the initial video of him urinating on that young girl came out. i found out about it because i was in a gay club on south beach and they played the fucking video remixed with his music. i could not believe it. that shit stuck with me forever. i thought to myself - well at least thatâ€™s the end of his career right? ha! thatâ€™s not how it works in a patriarchy especially when wrapped in capitalism. as long as you can still make people money - you are still valuable. exploit and abuse women - no problem. exploit and abuse young black women - even less of a problem. thatâ€™s the reality of what we are seeing so clearly illustrated right now. pay attention to how it works...this is how we start to dismantle it. fuck r kelly. his studio is in chicago (at 219 n justine street). people know him. heâ€™s around town. just living his life. folks are holding #muterkelly protests at his studio. the police are investigating because they believe some of the women are being held there. #muterkelly #blm #blacklivesmatter #patriarchy #capitalism #feminism #feminist #craftivism #craftivist #badasscrossstitch #resist #metoo #timeisup

text:
#twft52 week 2 - swipe for instructions, starter questions, my response: "the word for this is sense." âœ’ğŸ–¤
@thewordforthis * * * 
a child who knew things, who saw a croneâ€™s face iridescent in a doorknob (they didnâ€™t believe) warning me of him; asked about the red building around the next bend of a road not yet visited (how did she know?); predicted the moment (does it light up?) when monuments illuminated at twilight. * * * 
as many youngsters do, i had countless extrasensory and telepathic experiences. no poltergeists, no angry voices. i simply remember knowing things i had no way to know (i still do). as is often the case, adults explained away, to suit their comfort. 
three memories, working backwards: 
i was 10, a dc weekend. the mall, periwinkle sky, the obelisk of the washington monument; i felt its connection between earth and sky. skeptical: â€œdoes this thing light up at night?â€ the split second after, a whoosh of energy, floodlights. even today my father marvels at my timing; i never told them what else i saw: a vortex of energy, particles streaming up and out, around and down, back up through this divining rod they insisted was solid concrete. i knew about the billions of tiny pockets of space in cement, knew that things happened in there. 
age 6, driving to visit relatives i barely knew. â€œthereâ€™s a big red building on the left.â€ my father at the wheel, a brief exchange, the bend in the road, the structure in question. weâ€™d never taken that route before. 
and age 3. the bath off the kitchen, flocked wallpaper, door directly in front of the toilet. mid-morning, mind wandering, the brass doorknob morphs to a wizened face, colors like the oil slick on the driveway after the rain. the words i tried to tell my mother as she stood at the kitchen sink: â€œgrandpa is no.â€ i couldnâ€™t convince her iâ€™d been wide awake; i didnâ€™t try for long. 
maybe the crone was me, decades from now, when energy leaves this body, another time and space, wherever, whenever iâ€™m supposed to be.

repost from @theconsciouskid "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
backstage at carmen with female lead lucia! had the pleasure of attending one of the most famous operas of all time, bizet's carmen presented by the kitchener waterloo-symphony. sold out show tonight! 
andrie feher, conductor, lucia cervoni, mezzo soprano ernesto ramirez, tenor, alexander dobson, baritone ...lucia rocked it! this was an extra special evening as it featured over 150 wilfrid laurier university faculty of music students, instructors and alumni, which brought so much energy along with a stage of young children who also sang a song in french! carmen: what a powerful role for a woman to play on stage, the theme of the 1930â€™s between genders and exploring freedom â€œla liberteâ€ is still so timely today with whatâ€™s happening in todayâ€™s #metoo movement. a choice to live a free life at that time as a woman and a bohemian life was a difficult one. bise makes you feel all things about what it means to have freedom of choice and expression and speak up instead of being suppressed. are we allowed to be free and live the life we wish? ğŸ’ƒğŸ’‹ğŸ’„got to get a hug and smile back stage with friends and family and the amazing lucia cervoni... if you have connections to the opera in your hometown town i suggest you put in a request lucia to perform! wow! her performance was very powerful, charismatic and moving! #femalelead role woman to watch out for lucia cervoni, ernesto ramirez #opera #operacarmen #femaleleadrole #femalelead #metoomovement #bizet #bizetcarmen #boheme #bohemianlife #freedomtolove #femaleoperalead #lifeofastar #operasingerlife
